<HEADLINE>
<P>
JERRY HULSE'S TRAVEL TIPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hulse 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Soon the leaf peepers will be out in force as the spectacle of the fall foliage 
season gets underway in Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Rhode 
Island and Vermont. Country inns throughout the New England states will be 
welcoming guests by the thousands. To assist travelers planning independent 
tours, a list of inns is available from New England B&amp;B, 1045 Centre St., 
Newton Centre, Mass. 02159. Telephone (617) 244-2112. Others can be obtained 
from New England U.S.A., 76 Summer St., Boston, Mass. 02110 (free sightseeing 
maps of New England states plus a travel planner). 
</P>
<P>
Other Sources 
</P>
<P>
 -- Connecticut Department of Economic Development, 210 Washington St., 
Hartford, Conn. 06106. Telephone (203) 566-3385. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Massachusetts Office of Travel &amp; Tourism, 100 Cambridge St., 13th 
Floor, Boston, Mass. 02202. Telephone (617) 727-3201. (Ask for a copy of the 
"Spirit of Massachusetts Guide.") 
</P>
<P>
 -- Maine Division of Tourism, 189 State St., No. 59, Augusta, Me. 04333. 
Telephone (207) 289-5710. 
</P>
<P>
 -- New Hampshire Office of Vacation Travel, P.O. Box 856, Concord, N.H. 03301. 
Telephone (603) 271-2666. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Rhode Island Division of Tourism, 7 Jackson Walkway, Providence, R.I. 
02903. Telephone (401) 277-2601. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Vermont Travel Division, 134 State St., Montpelier, Vt. 05601. Telephone 
(802) 828-3236. 
</P>
<P>
Tours 
</P>
<P>
Your travel agent will help you arrange conducted/independent tours of New 
England. For names of California agencies specializing in New England tours, 
write to Jerry Di Pitro, c/o Tourco, 712 Main St., Hyannis, Mass. 02601. Di 
Pitro is one of New England's major tour operators. One of his offerings is an 
eight-day motor-coach trip through New England for $890 (includes lodging, 
ground transportation, some meals). 
</P>
<P>
 -- Tauk Tours is considered the Rolls-Royce of tour operators. A wide range of 
rates. Write to Tauk Tours, P.O. Box 5027, Westport, Conn. 06881. Or call 
toll-free (800) 468-2825. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Yankee Holidays, 20 Spring St., Saugus, Mass. 01906. Call toll-free (800) 
225-2550. A choice of day-tours out of Boston, with visits to Maine, New 
Hampshire, Rhode Island. The same company is featuring a "Taste of Boston" tour 
with dinners at an Italian restaurant only steps from Paul Revere's home and 
the Old North Church, and seafood at the renowned Skipjack's restaurant in 
historic Copley Square. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Domenico Tours, 751 Broadway, Bayonne, N.J. 07002. Telephone toll-free 
(800) 554-8687. Does a volume business. Prices run the scale from $189 up. An 
11-day grand tour figures out to $899 (Boston to Cape Cod, New Hampshire, 
Vermont, Canada, Niagara, with a windup in New York). Dozens of variations. A 
five-day Boston-Cape Cod-Martha's Vineyard trip will cost you $419. A total of 
35 tours scheduled during September/October. Details in a 40-page fall foliage 
booklet. 
</P>
<P>
Leafer's Guide 
</P>
<P>
For a "leaf peepers guide," contact the White Mountains Attraction Assn., Box 
176, North Woodstock, N.H. 03262. This handy little brochure tells how leaves 
change color and puts to rest that old wives' tale about Jack Frost being 
responsible for the brilliance of autumn colors. The guide advises that the 
foliage season in New Hampshire generally begins in late September, continues 
into the first week of October in northern New Hampshire, with colors peaking 
in southern New Hampshire between Oct. 5 and 15. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Country stores, a Norman Rockwell exhibition, horse farms and a maple 
museum are listed in a free "Vermont Attractions" guide. Copies from Vermont 
Travel Division, 134 State St., Montpellier, Vt. 05602. 
</P>
<P>
 -- For a brochure highlighting the Shelburne Museum (displays a side-wheeler, 
steam train, period furniture, carriages, weather vanes, scrimshaw), send a 
post card to Shelburne, Vt. 05482. 
</P>
<P>
Vermont Inns 
</P>
<P>
Vermont Marble Inn, 12 W. Park Place, Fair Haven, Vt. 05743. Telephone (802) 
265-8383. Rates: $75/$108. Fourteen guest rooms (three with marble fireplaces). 
Faces the village green on a five-acre plot. Fresh produce, home baking, an 
extensive wine list. 
</P>
<P>
The Inn At Sawmill Farm, Box 367, Mt. Snow Valley, West Dover, Vt. 05356. 
Telephone (802) 464-8131. Rates: $220/$260 (two persons) with breakfast/dinner. 
</P>
<P>
The Quilted Cat, Rural Route 1, Box 201A, Andover, Vt. 05143. Telephone (802) 
875-2724. Rates: $80/$125. 
</P>
<P>
Old Tavern At Grafton, Grafton, Vt. 05146. Telephone (802) 843-2231. Rates: 
$70/$120. 
</P>
<P>
The Golden Stage Inn, P.O. Box 218, Proctorville, Vt. 05153. Telephone (802) 
226-7744. Rates: $155 (two persons), including breakfast and dinner. 
</P>
<P>
New Hampshire Inns 
</P>
<P>
Covered Bridge Inn, Route 302, Glen, N.H. 03838. Telephone (603) 383-9109. 
Rates: $29/$39 per person, double. (The only inn in New England with its own 
covered bridge. Five guest rooms. Near five major ski areas. A gift shop 
operated by the owners contains hundreds of craft items.) 
</P>
<P>
Covered Bridge House, Route 302, Glen, N.H. 03838. Telephone (603) 383-9109. 
</P>
<P>
Connecticut Inns 
</P>
<P>
Constitution Oak Farm, Beardsley Road, Kent, Conn. 06757. Telephone (203) 
354-6495. Four rooms. Rates: $45/$55. An old-fashioned farmhouse with dairy 
cattle, open pasture. About a mile from Lake Waramaug (90 miles outside New 
York City). 
</P>
<P>
Copper Beech Inn, Main St., Ivoryton, Conn. 06442. Telephone (203) 767-0330. 
Rates: $95/$155. 
</P>
<P>
Griswold Inn, Main St., Essex, Conn. 06426. Telephone (203) 767-1812. Rates: 
$75/$165. 
</P>
