<HEADLINE>
<P>
WATCHING WATCHERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
People in the media are in the business of selling illusion; but, increasingly, 
they are beginning to believe the illusions themselves. 
</P>
<P>
Such was the case when Daniel Cerone asked television critics "What America 
Watches -- and Why" (Aug. 6). To believe that TV critics are authorities on 
what motivates viewers to watch one program over another is to put up mirrors 
and smoke screens. What is more interesting is how such critics themselves 
influence what America watches. Indeed, TV critics create self-fulfilling 
prophecies by telling the public what they are going to like or dislike and 
why. 
</P>
<P>
CAROLE LIEBERMAN, MD 
</P>
<P>
Malibu 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA082089-0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 96964 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 20, 1989, Sunday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
